[color=#40BF00][size=150]Short list of features[/size][/color]


[list]
[*]Many keyboard bindings, different for Russian and English layouts ([c]RAlt + F1 toggle on/off[/c]), e.g.: [c]RAlt + A[/c] → Ă, [c]RAlt + O[/c] → Ø; [c]RAlt + Ф[/c] → Ѳ, [c]RAlt + Щ[/c] → Ҩ. Supports user-defined bindings.
[*]“Compositing” mode ([c]RAlt×2[/c]) that allows converting symbol sequences into another symbol, e.g.: [c]TH[/c] → Þ, [c]WY[/c] → Ƿ, [c]1/10[/c] → ⅒ etc. Has a tooltip with suggestions of matching sequences. Supports user-defined sequences.
[*]“Alternative modes” ([c]LWin + LAlt + S[/c]), a feature that supports the aforementioned writing systems.
[*]“Glyph variations” ([c]LWin + LAlt + A[/c]), allows typing variants of characters, e.g.: A → ᴬ𝐀𝘼𝙰𝕬𝓐 etc.
[*]“TELEX/VNI-like modes” ([c]LWin + LAlt + D[/c]), simplifies typing of Vietnamese, Jarai and Pinyin with input similar to Vietnamese Telex and VNI layouts.
[*]Switching between typing Unicode character → HTML → LaTeX command ([c]RAlt + RShift + F1[/c]), e.g.: [c]Ă[/c] → [c]&Abreve;[/c] → [c]\u{A}[/c]. Has a tooltip with suggestions of matching sequences.
[*]Search and insert symbols by “tags” ([c]LWin + LAlt + F[/c]), e.g.: prompt “plus minus” gives “±”.
[*]“Internal” keyboard layouts with support for user-defined layouts.
[*]Mini-modes for typing super/subscript ([c]LWin + LAlt + ↑/↓[/c]) digits and roman numerals ([c]LWin + LAlt + RShift + ↑[/c]).
[*]Favorites system that adds favorited symbols to the “Favorites” tab in the main GUI and shows their sequences in the “Composite“ mode tooltip.
[*]Support for modifications. For example, you are allowed to add a new “Alternative mode” with new symbols (e.g., “Old Mongolian”).
[*]And other, less significant features…
[*]GUI Windows: Lists of symbols (binds, sequences etc.) and help ([c]LWin + LAlt + Home[/c]); Glyph Variations; User-defined sequences; Mods; “Legend”; Settings ([c]RCtrl + F9[/c]) etc. All of these are available to be opened from the tray context menu.
[/list]



[color=#40BF00][size=150]Multi-layer Bindings, also known as “Fast Keys”[/size][/color]

The most terrifying part. There are many of them, incredibly many, and an experienced pianist will undoubtedly handle them. If we trust [c].HotKeysCount()[/c], there are more than eight hundred of them. Each key can have up to 10-11 possible combinations (not counting combinations with active CapsLock as separate ones), but on average there are about eight (Latin I is the champion here: Ĭ Ï Ī Ĩ Î Ǐ Į İ Í Ì Ȉ).


[spoiler2="Details"]

If necessary, they can be disabled/enabled via [c]RAlt + F1[/c]. The state is saved in the settings file.

The tool was created for a full-size keyboard — with arrows, numpad, etc. This may cause inconvenience for users of other keyboard variants, however this can be smoothed out through custom bindings.

Some combinations were inherited from the Ilya Birman’s “[url=https://ilyabirman.net/typography-layout]Typographic Layout[/url]”:

[list]
[*][c]RAlt + /[/c] — enters ellipsis [ … ],
[*][c]RAlt + 1 | 7[/c] — enter inverted exclamation and question marks [ ¡ ¿ ],
[*][c]RAlt + 5[/c] — enters per mille [ ‰ ],
[*][c]RAlt LAlt + 8[/c] — enters infinity symbol [ ∞ ] (the original combination was taken by the multiplication symbol [ × ], so left Alt was added to the combination for infinity),
[*][c]RAlt *(LShift) + Hyphen-minus[/c] — enter em dash and en dash [ — – ],
[*][c]RAlt + Equals[/c] — not equal [ ≠ ],
[*][c]RAlt + Space[/c] — non-breaking space [ [u] [/u] ].
[/list]

Combinations for inserting quotation marks are inherited as [c]Б (<)[/c] and [c]Ю (>)[/c] as in the “Typographic Layout”, but have slightly different behavior:

[list]
[*][c]RAlt + Б (<) | Ю (>)[/c] — enter [ « » ] if Russian is active, or [ “ ” ] if English is active,
[*][c]RAlt LAlt + Б (<) | Ю (>)[/c] — same as previous, but languages are swapped,
[*][c]RAlt LShift + Б (<) | Ю (>)[/c] — enter [ „ “ ] if Russian is active, or [ ‘ ’ ] if English is active,
[*][c]RAlt RShift + Ё (`)[/c] — additional combination for [ ’ ] for use as an apostrophe.
[/list]

Examples of tool’s own bindings:

[list]
[*][c]RAlt + Arrow keys[/c] — [ ←↑↓→ ],
[*][c]RAlt + Arrow key pairs (left-up, right-up, left-down, etc.)[/c] — [ ↖↗↙↘↔↕ ],
[*][c]RAlt LShift + Arrow keys[/c] — [ ⮌⮍⮏⮎ ],
[*][c]RAlt RShift + Left/Right arrow keys[/c] — [ ↺↻ ],
[*][c]RAlt RShift + Space[/c] — em space [ [u] [/u] ],
[*][c]RAlt LShift + Space[/c] — en space [ [u] [/u] ],
[*][c]RAlt LAlt + Space[/c] — thin space [ [u] [/u] ],
[*][c]RAlt + 9 | 0[/c] — [ ⟨ ⟩ ],
[*][c]RAlt + [ | ][/c] — [ ⁅ ⁆ ],
[*][c]RAlt LAlt LShift RShift + [ | ][/c] — [ 《 》 ],
[*][c]RShift *(CapsLock) + 1[/c] — [ ‽ ⸘ ].
[/list]

Combinations that will not be displayed in the interface:

[list]
[*][c]Shift + 2, 3, 4, 6, 7[/c] are mirrored for languages on [c]RShift[/c], i.e. in English [c]LShift + 2[/c] will enter [ @ ] (as usual), and [c]RShift + 2[/c] — [ " ], in Russian — vice versa. [c]2 (@"), 3 (#№), 4 ($;), 6 (^:), 7 (&?)[/c].
[*][c]RShift *(LShift) + Х, Ъ[/c] will enter brackets [] and {} respectively.
[/list]

There are also “Secondary” and “Tertiary keys”, activated via [c]RAlt LAlt + F1[/c] and [c]RAlt LAlt + F2[/c]. These are additional bindings for symbols that didn’t fit into the main pool, but really wanted to. They came to replace the very first, rejected “mechanic” of the tool — “Activation Groups”: it was necessary to press a combination to activate one of the “groups”, and then enter the symbolic key of the desired character.

These keys are disabled by pressing their combination again, and the state is saved in the settings file.

