[color=#40BF00][size=150]Compositing mode[/size][/color]

Inspired by the Compose key from Linux and WinCompose. Converts a sequence of symbols into something else.

Activated by double-pressing [c]RAlt[/c]. User input will be displayed in a tooltip along with matching suggestions and a list of favorite symbol recipes.

[img]https://raw.githubusercontent.com/DemerNkardaz/DSL-KeyPad-Docs/refs/heads/main/Media/compose_demo.webp[/img]


[spoiler2="Details"]

Compose mode triggers on the first exact recipe match. This is both a plus and a slight minus — such behavior won’t allow typing, for example, [c]Ǣ[/c] due to the automatic triggering of [c]AE[/c] → [c]Æ[/c]. To solve this problem, I introduced a hold mode ([c]Pause[/c] key), in which composition waits for [c]Enter[/c] to be pressed or for the hold to be released.

In addition to hold mode, you can use the grave “operator” [c] ` [/c]. It doesn’t cancel automatic triggering, but saves its result in the active composition variable instead of sending it to the application window. This allows continuing sequences if there are recipes that start with the obtained result. [c]Ǣ[/c] = [c]A`E → Æ → Æ<MACRON>[/c].

General key list:

[list]
[*][c]Enter[/c] — confirm input.
[*][c]Escape[/c] — cancel compose mode.
[*][c]Backspace[/c] — delete the last character.
[*][c]Insert[/c] — paste clipboard contents.
[*][c]Pause[/c] — toggle hold mode.
[/list]

[b]Operators[/b]

[list]
[*]Grave [c] ` [/c] — described above.
[*]([c]NUMBER[/c]) — when starting input with this operator, the recipe result will be duplicated the specified number of times, “(5) TH” → “ÞÞÞÞÞ”.
[*]([c]~[/c]) — when starting input with this operator, you can enter whole words within which recipes will be processed, “[c](~) T<COMMA>ara Roma<CIRCUMFLEX>neasca<BREVE>[/c]” → “Țara Românească“.
[*]([c]NUMBER~[/c]) — combination of the previous operators.
[*][c]##[/c] — allows preventing processing of unwanted sequences, “[c](~) tho<ACUTE>rr” → “þórr”, “(\~) t##ho<ACUTE>rr[/c]” → “thórr”.
[/list]

[b]Unicode Codepoint and Alt-code Input[/b]

Compose mode can be used to insert symbols by their codes. Input starts with U+/Ю+ or A+/А+, followed by the value. You can specify multiple values by separating them with spaces.

Alt-codes are affected by the active layout language: numbers 128–255 and 0128–0255 use codepages 850/Windows−1252 for English layout, 866/Windows−1251 for Russian, 737/Windows−1253 for Greek, Windows−1258 for Vietnamese.

Alt-codes can be entered in hexadecimal format: [c]A+0B9[/c] = [c]A+0185[/c] → № (Windows−1251). For this, the input must contain a letter from the A–F range. The upper limit is A+FF (A+255).

